===Etymology===
Middle English ''[[windels]]'' or ''[[windas]]'', Old Norse ''[[vindass]]'', from ''[[vinda]]'', "to wind", + ''[[ass]]'', "pole". Confer Icelandic ''[[vindilass]]''.
===Noun===
'''windlass''' (''plural'' '''[[windlasses]]''')

# {{nautical}} A type of [[winch]], fitted with a [[gipsy]] for [[haul]]ing [[chain]] [[cable]], or a [[drum]] for [[rope]].
# {{nautical}} An [[apparatus]] in which horizontal or vertical drums or wheels are operated by means of a steam engine, pneumatic engine, hydraulic engine, or electric motor for handling heavy anchor chains, hawsers, etc. (FM 55-501]]

